Why this task is smaller than it looks:

The real "tmux attach + downgrade indicator" feature has three layers:
1. Backend: surface the state (budget degraded_model, harness tmux
   availability)
2. Frontend: render an affordance
3. Frontend: when clicked, stream a terminal

This commit lands layers 1 and 2 fully. Layer 3 (the xterm.js +
WebSocket terminal stream) is honest deferred work — it requires a
harness that actually exposes a tmux session over a socket we can
bridge to the browser, and no harness does today. Shipping the button
without layer 3 would leave a non-functional UI element in the app;
hiding the button until `available: true` means the UI surface only
appears when it will work.

**Why extend /api/budget/:id instead of adding a new endpoint.**
The frontend already fetches budget for the agent detail pages. Adding
`degraded_model` + `is_paused` to the existing response means one
HTTP call for the UI, not two. The BudgetSummary stays unchanged for
other callers (budget table, history), and the new fields are
additive. Future-proofing: if we want a full BudgetState on the API,
upgrade this endpoint rather than adding more.

**Why `agentHarness.tmux` is a separate helper, not on `agents.*`.**
The `agents` object in the API client is about agent CRUD. Tmux
availability is a harness-capability query that happens to be keyed
by agent id — the reasoning flows through the harness, not the agent
record. Grouping by `agentHarness` leaves room for other capability
queries (`.snapshot(id)`, `.restore(id, snap)`) without overloading
the agents namespace.

**The `untrack()` around budget/tmux fetches inside the $effect.**
Without untrack, every time a fetch resolves and sets `primaryBudget`,
Svelte's reactive system sees that as a dependency of the effect and
re-runs it, causing an infinite fetch loop. Untracking the actual
fetch body (and double-checking `primaryAgentId === id` inside the
`.then` in case the user navigated away mid-flight) keeps it correct.

**Why the tmux button alerts instead of opening a real view.**
xterm.js hasn't been pulled in as a dep yet; if I added it now I'd
also have to build the WebSocket streaming endpoint server-side. That
work is meaningful and belongs with a harness that has an actual tmux
session to show — doing it now against nothing would be plumbing for
plumbing's sake. The alert() is a visible "not wired yet" marker that
makes it obvious which piece is still missing when someone eventually
clicks it.

**The DockerUnavailable enum variant still leaks through in agents.rs
fallbacks.**
When `state.harness()` returns None we report `ObservedStatus::
DockerUnavailable`. The name is stale (Docker is gone) but the
serialized string is what frontend callers see, and renaming it would
ripple through their type checks. Follow-up task 7 phase C (the setup
wizard cleanup) is a natural place to also rename the enum once the
UI churn is already happening.

**Why `budget.agent(id)` uses encodeURIComponent even though agent ids
are currently plain strings.**
Defensive — agent ids could contain `/` or other URL-significant
characters in the future (e.g. namespaced ids like `team-a/atlas`).
The cost is zero and the correctness win is real.

**What a real user will see today if they run this.**
The downgrade chip will ONLY show if something manually seeds
`degraded_model` in the agent's budget_state row (no real degrade flow
runs to completion in the spike — agents don't launch). A manual test:
insert the row and refresh the conversation page, chip appears. The
tmux button never shows because no harness implements `attach_tmux`.
